DigitalDescription: Concerns about a stroke, TIA or mini stroke.

DigitalTitles: Genital injury with cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the genitals within the last 7 days that has cut the skin. Cuts, wounds or grazes anywhere on the vagina or the area between the anus and vagina.

DigitalTitles: Genital injury with cut or wound
DigitalDescription: Cuts, wounds or grazes to the penis, scrotum, testicles or the area between the anus and scrotum, within the last 7 days.
Feeling the heart is beating too fast or too slow. Pounding or irregular heartbeat. Racing heart, fluttering in the chest, skipped beats.

DigitalTitles: Swallowed or breathed in an object
DigitalDescription: Accidentally swallowing or inhaling something. Choking or inhaling an object. Something stuck in the throat.
A blocked or runny nose, sneezing, aching muscles, headaches, pain in the face and coughing.
A problem with the sinuses. Face pain around the cheeks, eyes or forehead. A runny nose and a high temperature.
Feeling tired or exhausted (fatigue) most of the time, or tiring easily.

DigitalTitles: Bottom pain, swelling lump or itch
DigitalDescription: Pain, itching or swelling in or around the bum (anus or rectum). Lumps in or around the bottom.
Dirt, dust or an object has gone into the eyes. Something sprayed or splashed into the eyes.
Any lump, cyst, swelling or pain in or around the vagina. Swollen or sore labia.
Problems getting the baby to attach to the breast. Cracked or sore nipples, or a painful breast that is making breastfeeding difficult.

DigitalTitles: Genital injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury anywhere on the genitals in the last 7 days that hasn't cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Genital injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the penis, scrotum, testicles or between the anus and scrotum, within the last 7 days, that has not cut the skin.
Ache or stiffness in one or both shoulders. Unusual feelings or weakness.
Can't poo or finding it hard to poo, with or without tummy pain.
Pain or swelling in the arm or elbow.

DigitalTitles: Leg injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the leg, hip, thigh, knee, calf, shin or ankle in the last 7 days, that has a cut, wound or graze.

DigitalTitles: Leg injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: A leg injury above the ankle, within the last 7 days, that didn't cut the skin.
A problem with a small object stuck in the skin. Wood or glass splinters. Problems with piercings.

DigitalTitles: Hand or wrist injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the hand or wrist within the last 7 days that has cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Finger or thumb injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: A finger or thumb injury within the last 7 days that has cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Hand or wrist injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: A hand or wrist injury in the last 7 days that hasn't cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Finger or thumb injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: A finger or thumb injury within the last 7 days that hasn't cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Toe injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: A toe injury within the last 7 days that hasn't  cut the skin.
Something is glued to the skin, or the skin has been glued together.
Mouth, lip, tongue or gum ulcers. Sore white or grey patches inside the mouth.
Having trouble swallowing or unable to swallow, without a sore throat

DigitalTitles: Ankle or foot injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the ankle or foot that doesn't have any type of cut or wound. Sprained ankle.

DigitalTitles: Ankle or foot injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the ankle or foot that has any type of cut or wound.

DigitalTitles: Toe injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to one or more toes within the last 7 days that has cut the skin.
An object stuck inside the ear. An insect in the ear.
An object stuck inside a nostril.

DigitalTitles: Something stuck in or around the penis
DigitalDescription: An object stuck inside or around the penis.
An object stuck in the back passage.
An item such as a tampon, cap, condom or other object, that's got stuck in the vagina.
Self-harm (eg cutting, burning, substance abuse, anorexia or bulimia) as a way of dealing with difficult feelings. Swallowing, breathing in or injecting something poisionous on purpose.

DigitalTitles: Swollen or painful face or neck
DigitalDescription: Swelling, lumps or pain in the face or neck. Swollen glands.
Too much to drink. Being sick or feeling ill because of alcoholic drinks.
Runny or watery poo and being sick, with or without tummy pain.
Sore or itchy vagina.
Male genital problems, with or without tummy pain.
A problem with a blocked or leaking catheter. Pain from a catheter. Trouble removing or inserting a catheter.
Any injury to the fingernail or nails in the last 7 days.
Any bite or sting from animals, humans, insects, reptiles or water creatures. Bitten by a pet or wild animal.
A small cut, scratch or graze that might have gravel, dirt or grit inside.
An injury to one or more toenails within the last 7 days. Painful, broken, ingrown or loose toenails.

DigitalTitles: Lower back injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the lower back (below the rib cage) or bottom in the last 7 days that hasn't cut the skin.
Any problems with the breast or nipple. Lumps, pain or any worries about skin changes.

DigitalTitles: Toothache, swelling and other dental problems
DigitalDescription: Bleeding from the mouth, teeth or gums. Painful  teeth or gums. Swelling or lumps on the gums, mouth or jaw. A crown, bridge, fillings, denture or brace problem. A broken tooth, or teeth not caused by an injury.

DigitalTitles: Swollen or painful hand, finger or wrist
DigitalDescription: Pain or swelling in the hand, fingers, nails or wrist.
Blisters from something rubbing against the skin, such as new shoes.
Sore, yellow, red or bloodshot eyes. Loss of or changes in vision. Swollen, sticky, itchy or sore eyelids. A lump on the eyelid.
CommonTerms: blood in white of the eye

DigitalDescription: Coughing up blood in sick (vomit), phlegm or mucus.
Late or missed periods. No periods. Periods haven't started. Periods have stopped.
Hair loss from any part of the body. Losing hair in patches or clumps.
Strange feelings in the skin anywhere on the body. Numbness, burning, tingling or pins and needles.
Physical or emotional problems with sexual health or sexuality. Worries about sexually transmitted infections (STIs), HIV/AIDs. Premenstrual symptoms (PMT/PMS). Menopause.
A physical or emotional problem with sexual health or activity. Worries about sexually transmitted infections (STIs), HIV/AIDS
Problems sleeping, getting to sleep or staying asleep. Tiredness. Insomnia.

DigitalTitles: Fluid or wax coming from the ear with no loss of hearing
DigitalDescription: Fluid, ear wax or watery discharge from one or both ears but without any loss of hearing.

DigitalTitles: Problems with wounds, plaster casts or metal rods
DigitalDescription: New problems from a wound that has already been treated by a doctor or nurse. Pain or problems with stitches, staples, plaster casts, metal rods or drainage tubes.
Problems opening or closing the mouth or jaw.
A bleeding nose following an injury.
A problem with any stoma or bag attached to the body.

DigitalTitles: Cold arm or arm changing colour
DigitalDescription: A cold, painless arm. White, blue, or black colour in one or both arms.

DigitalTitles: Cold leg or leg changing colour
DigitalDescription: A cold, painless leg. White, blue or black colour in one or both legs.
Diabetic blood sugar levels are too high or too low. A sudden problem with blood sugar levels.
Any odd behaviour. Seeing or hearing things that aren’t there. Can't stay awake. New changes or an existing condition getting worse.
Low mood, feeling depressed or stressed. Panic attacks or anxiety. Trouble sleeping. Seeing or hearing things that aren't there. Drink and drug problems.
An urge to poo that can't be controlled. Soiling or staining underwear. May also include constipation or diarrhoea, bloating or wind.
Hearing problems or deafness without earache. Blocked ear or fluid leaking from the ear with no pain.

DigitalTitles: Can't feel baby move as much
DigitalDescription: Worries that the baby isn't moving as much as usual. Baby's movements are slower or have stopped.
Shaking or trembling (tremor).

DigitalTitles: Rashes, itchy skin, spots or blisters
DigitalDescription: Skin problems (including moles). Eczema or ringworm. Scabies, lice or athlete's foot. Chickenpox or shingles. Lumps, bruises or yellow skin. Problems with birthmarks and tattoos.
Hiccups, with possible fever. Hiccups won't stop.
A problem with wound (that had been seen by a nurse or doctor). The wound is more than 7 days old.

DigitalTitles: Stomach or side injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the tummy (abdomen), or sides (flank) within the last 7 days that hasn't cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Injury to the stomach or side of body with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the tummy (abdomen), or sides (flank) within the last 7 days that has cut the skin.
Tummy (abdominal) pain with or without other symptoms such as diarrhoea, vomiting or a high temperature.
Chest, rib or upper back pain when breathing. Wheezing, panting or feeling out of breath. Difficult or noisy breathing.
Burns caused by chemicals.

Toothache and pain caused by an injury, such as broken, cracked or knocked out teeth. Bleeding or injuries to the gums or mouth. Swelling or lumps on the face or jaw. Problems opening or closing the mouth.
A scald from hot liquid or a burn from touching something hot, such as an iron or a flame.

DigitalTitles: Chest or upper back injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the chest or upper back within the last 7 days, that hasn't cut the skin. Injuries from the collarbone to bottom of the ribcage.

DigitalTitles: Chest or upper back injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the chest or upper back (the collarbone to the bottom of the ribcage) within the last 7 days that has cut the skin.
Dental problems caused by an injury, such as knocked out or broken teeth. Injuries to the gums or the inside of the mouth.
Runny or watery poo, with or without pain in the tummy.
Feeling dizzy, off balance, lightheaded or as if the room is spinning (vertigo).
Pain, stinging or burning while weeing (passing urine). Weeing too often or smelly wee.
Ear pain, swelling, or fluid leaking from the ear. A painful blocked ear. New deafness with pain. Ringing in the ear.

DigitalTitles: Eye injury without cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the eye or eye socket within the last 7 days without any cut or wound.
An injury to the eye or eye socket within the last 7 days that has caused a cut or wound.

DigitalTitles: Head, face or neck injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the head, face or neck within the last 7 days that didn't cut the skin.

DigitalTitles: Head, face or neck injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to any part of the face (but not eyes or teeth), head or neck, which has cut the skin, within the last 7 days.
A fall, faint, blackout or loss of consciousness, with no injury.
Chills and shivering, or hot to touch. A high temperature, with no other symptoms.

DigitalTitles: Pain in the side of the body
DigitalDescription: Pain on either side of the body, between the ribs and hips. Affecting one side only at the back (love handles) or with stomach pain.
Pain or swelling in the groin (between the waist and upper thighs).
Throbbing or intense pain or a tight band around the head. Visual problems like flashing lights with a headache.

DigitalTitles: Swollen or painful legs, knees, ankles or feet
DigitalDescription: Painful or swollen legs, knees, ankles or feet. Pain or swelling in the hips, backside or buttocks.
Pain or ache in the lower part of the back.

DigitalTitles: Lower back injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the lower back (below the rib cage) or bottom in the last 7 days with a cut, wound or graze.
A bleeding nose.
Spots of blood on the toilet paper. Streaks of blood in poo. Red or black coloured poo.
A painful throat, with or without problems swallowing. A hoarse, croaky or lost voice, with or without a sore throat.

DigitalTitles: Accidental overdose or taking something harmful
DigitalDescription: Accidentally taking, swallowing, breathing in or injecting something poisonous. Taking too many painkillers or an overdose of medicine like insulin.
CommonTerms: breathing in or swallowing something poisonous

DigitalDescription: Problems with weeing (passing urine), such as only being able to wee very small amounts, or can't wee at all.

DigitalTitles: Arm injury without a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the arm, wrist or shoulder within the last 7 days, that has not cut the skin. A dislocated shoulder or arm.

DigitalTitles: Arm injury with a cut or wound
DigitalDescription: An injury to the arm or shoulder in the last 7 days, that has caused a cut or wound.
Heavy periods, bleeding after sex or unexpected bleeding. Bleeding or spotting when pregnant.
Vaginal discharge, with or without tummy pain.
Being or feeling sick.
Bloody, red or pink wee (urine)
Hacking, tickly or dry cough, without other cold symptoms. Coughing up phlegm or mucus.
A congested or blocked nose. Sinus problems.
Burns caused by the sun or a tanning sunbed or lamp. Red, warm, sore, tender, or peeling skin.
Overheating caused by being in hot temperatures or by exercising too much.
